history.content:
There's nothing about circuits in 127. It's an applied math class assuming you had a solid background in linear algebra. They do teach you Linear Algebra again for the first 1/3 of the class but it goes really fast. 

Prof. Alex Bayen is an amazing lecturer--one of the best I've ever seen in my life. I took his 127 last semester and his lectures were clear to understand, full of humor and dynamic, and at the same time covered all the key points of the material that you need to know.

Homework sometimes can be hard and time-consuming but in general, it's not bad if you have a good math intuition, as the homework is majorly long math problem set. Taking math53, math54, math110, 16AB will definitely help with the class, but it's ok if you don't since it's a pretty self-contained class.

Exams can be hard but they do curve the class.

I know it's an EECS class, but I'm not at all interested in learning about circuits. Does 127 use/teach a lot of circuit stuff? I just want the math and skills to optimize general problems. 

Also, if anyone can talk about their experience learning from the professor (Alexandre Bayen) I'd appreciate hearing them. 

Also also, what does the time commitment look like? 

Thanks!
